@arg vsatelier/cluster-as-agenda
@title Cluster as Agenda Item
@sigils [📋/议]

! conclusion: Allow participants to flag spatial clusters or arc concentrations as agenda items so that patterns visible in the constellation become inputs to structured deliberation.
  + context: You are bridging spatial perception and collective decision-making.
  + IF: Participants notice a recurring pattern — dense causal links, an isolated story, a shared harm.
  + HOWEVER: Without a mechanism to capture the observation and route it to deliberation, spatial insight dissipates.
  + THEN: Provide a "flag this pattern" gesture that captures the cluster and a framing question. The flag becomes an agenda item in a facilitation queue.
  + BECAUSE: Agendas grounded in visible spatial patterns carry their evidence with them.
  + STATUS: status[sketch]

@arg vsatelier/decision-provenance
@title Decision Provenance
@sigils [🔗/溯]

! conclusion: Every decision should trace back to the stories, links, and flagged patterns that motivated it, creating an auditable chain from lived experience to collective action.
  + context: You are designing accountability into a system where community stories inform real decisions.
  + IF: A facilitated session produces a decision — fund a programme, change a policy, create a new pilot.
  + HOWEVER: Decisions recorded without evidential context become assertions rather than conclusions.
  + THEN: Link each decision record to its agenda flag, source stories and arcs, session notes, and participants.
  + BECAUSE: Provenance is how deliberation becomes trustworthy.
  + STATUS: status[sketch]

@arg vsatelier/annotation-as-commitment
@title Annotation as Commitment
@sigils [✍️/约]

! conclusion: Interpretive notes should be able to graduate from observations into commitments — named actions with owners, timelines, and completion criteria.
  + context: You are designing the bridge between interpretation and action within a facilitated programme.
  + IF: A pilot's interpretive notes surface actionable patterns.
  + HOWEVER: Notes that remain observations create a culture of noticing without acting.
  + THEN: Allow any note to be promoted to a commitment with an owner, deadline, and success criterion.
  + BECAUSE: When annotation becomes commitment, the constellation becomes a planning surface for the future.
  + STATUS: status[sketch]

@arg vsatelier/return-loop
@title Return Loop (Outcomes as New Stories)
@sigils [🔄/返]

! conclusion: Outcomes of actions should re-enter the constellation as new stories, closing the loop between seeing, deciding, acting, and witnessing.
  + context: You are designing a living system where action feeds back into shared knowledge.
  + IF: A community acts on a pattern surfaced by the constellation.
  + HOWEVER: If the outcome is never recorded, the constellation becomes a static snapshot.
  + THEN: Structure outcome stories that re-enter as new nodes, with arcs from the decision record to the outcome.
  + BECAUSE: The return loop transforms the constellation from a diagnostic instrument into a learning cycle.
  + STATUS: status[sketch]

@arg vsatelier/projection-independence
@title Projection Independence
@sigils [🪞/映]

! conclusion: Deliberation patterns should be defined independently of rendering technology so they work across VR domes, AR overlays, 2D graphs, hypertext, and terminals.
  + context: You are designing for longevity across hardware generations.
  + IF: The patterns of connection, clustering, and deliberation outlive specific renderers.
  + HOWEVER: Coupling to one technology (A-Frame, a specific headset) means patterns die with it.
  + THEN: Define the deliberation layer as data structures and interaction contracts. Each projection surface implements the contract differently.
  + BECAUSE: Projection independence is how a pattern library outlives its first implementation.
  + STATUS: status[sketch]

@arg vsatelier/federated-cosmoses
@title Federated Cosmoses
@sigils [🌐/宇]

! conclusion: Multiple independent constellations should federate — each visible as a node in a meta-view — so separate organisations can maintain sovereignty while discovering cross-boundary patterns.
  + context: You are designing for a network of organisations that each run their own story worlds.
  + IF: Several organisations each maintain their own installations.
  + HOWEVER: Isolated installations cannot reveal patterns spanning organisational boundaries.
  + THEN: Define a federation protocol: each installation publishes a summary. A meta-constellation renders each as a node. Opt-in cross-boundary links bridge cosmoses when both parties consent.
  + BECAUSE: Federation preserves sovereignty while enabling emergent patterns at scale.
  + STATUS: status[sketch]

@arg vsatelier/session-as-rehearsal
@title Session as Rehearsal
@sigils [🎭/排]

! conclusion: Treat each facilitated session as a rehearsal — a bounded, low-stakes space where participants practise collective interpretation, deliberation, and commitment.
  + context: You are introducing deliberation practices to groups new to collective sense-making.
  + IF: Participants are new to interpreting linked stories and producing shared decisions.
  + HOWEVER: Jumping to consequential decisions in an unfamiliar medium risks poor outcomes.
  + THEN: Structure early sessions as rehearsals with small anthologies and low-stakes questions. Graduate to consequential sessions once the group has practised the cycle.
  + BECAUSE: An atelier is a place of practice before it is a place of production. Deliberation skills are learned through doing.
  + STATUS: status[sketch]
